Preserved Vegetable Shaobing is a type of street delicacy made from flour, preserved vegetable (meigancai) and other ingredients
It looks like a Chinese version of pizza without the meat
It is a special snack in Zhejiang Province
Its outer layer is crispy, and its inner layer is moist and fragrant.

Cantonese desserts aka tong sui are very popular among the Chinese
Tong sui can be literally translated to sugar water as it is usually referring to sweet soup
It is common to see Cantonese Restaurant serving tong sui after dinner
This Christmas, we teamed up with @soap.yummy to bring you Tong Sui Soap which are made from natural ingredients that can be eaten!üòã
Natural brand, Soap Yummy wishes to promote care for the environment by reducing plastic packaging and chemical use. Meanwhile, promoting Hong Kong specialties like Tofu Fa, Black Sesame Soup and Ginger Milk Pudding Soap... ‚ú®Yummy to the skin & Gentle to the earth‚ú®
Delivering handmade soaps and skincare that are natural and nutritious to skin and ultimately prevent pollution to mother nature

These life-sized terracotta army is a form of funerary art to protect Emperor Qin Shi Huang in his afterlife
Emperor Qin Shi Huang started working on his mausoleum right after ascended the throne
It is believed that in order for the burial site to remain a secret, Emperor Qin Shi Huang has thousands of the workers who built the Army buried alive with him
It took more than 700,000 over 36 years to build the elaborate tomb. Hundreds of skeletons have already been discovered in the pits where the Warriors stand guard
There were also skeletal remains of women, thought to be the Emperor's concubines for the Afterlife

üìçMati Temple, Gansuüá®üá≥ is not a popular destination for tourist touring around the Qinghai-Dunhuang route because it is out of the way of other places of interest. Do not be deterred though. The place is rich in history and simply looks magnificent. Within the grotto temple, be prepared to climb narrowly carved out stairs and tunnels. Adventurous stuff. Just opposite one of the Mati Temple Grottoes is Mount Qilian, a beautiful snowcapped mountain towering above the town and temples. Took a few hours to reach but it was all worth it. Highly recommended for adventurous people who likes to "climb here climb there".
üì∑Photo by @zifstagram
